# TypeScript Absolute Imports

## Context
- When importing modules in TypeScript files
- When refactoring or moving files between directories
- When creating new components or modules
- When managing dependencies across the project

## Requirements
- Use absolute imports from project root instead of relative imports
- Configure TypeScript paths in tsconfig.json for module resolution
- Organize imports by external dependencies first, then absolute internal imports
- Use consistent naming for import aliases that reflect project structure
- Avoid deep relative imports (../../..)
- Use consistent import style across the entire codebase

## Examples
<example>
// Good: Using absolute imports
import { Button } from '@/components/ui/Button';
import { formatDate } from '@/utils/date';
import { useAuth } from '@/hooks/useAuth';
</example>

<example type="invalid">
// Bad: Using relative imports
import { Button } from '../../components/ui/Button';
import { formatDate } from '../../../utils/date';
import { useAuth } from '../../../../hooks/useAuth';
</example>

## AI Optimization
- Automatically refactor imports to absolute format when editing files
- Suggest appropriate path aliases based on project structure
- Maintain consistent import ordering in files
- Validate that imports follow the absolute pattern

## Critical Rules
- Always use absolute imports starting with project root alias (@/, src/, etc.)
- Never use relative imports that navigate up multiple directory levels
- Always maintain consistent import ordering (external libs first, then internal)
- Never mix absolute and relative import styles in the same file
- Always ensure tsconfig.json properly configures path aliases for absolute imports 